<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-785-172  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 785 172.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  August 20 1990 v16 n16 p60(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Can ICL make money selling computers to the Soviets? (companyprofile)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Guterl, Frederick V.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>ICL, the computer subsidiary of British electronic equipmentmanufacturer STC plc, has entered into a joint venture with theSoviet Merchant Marine MORFLOT to make and sell microcomputers inthe Soviet Union.andP;  The jointly formed company, Marine ComputerSystems (MCS), sold 2,700 microcomputers to the Soviet Union in1989, most shipped from ICL's factories in England and assembledin Leningrad.andP;  The operation is not expected to add considerablyto STC's earnings or sales, but the venture is part of ICL'slong-term strategy of keeping close to potentially profitableEastern European markets.andP;  MORFLOT owns 40 percent of MCS andprovides a network of sales offices staffed by Soviet nationals;it also provides financing and is the company's largest customer.andO;ICL holds a 40 percent share in MCS and supplies themicrocomputers and other materials as well as western managementexpertise.andP;  The city of Leningrad holds the other 20 percent ofthe firm and provides the three-story office and factory used byMCS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   ICL PLC (joint ventures)MORFLOT (joint ventures)Marine Computer Systems (management).andO;Topic:     Joint VentureSoviet UnionElectronic IndustryMarketing StrategyCompany ProfileManufacturersOrganization StructureComputer industryMicrocomputers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   ICL's percentage of STC's revenue and operating profit: 1988 and1989. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>